var definitions = ['<h2>Estou me vestindo para a escola.</h2><div><strong>Estou</strong> This is the first-person singular of the present tense of the verb "estar" in Portuguese, which means "to be", typically used to indicate temporary states or locations. It corresponds to "I am" in English.</div><div><strong>me</strong> This is a reflexive pronoun that corresponds to "myself" in English. It’s used here with the reflexive verb "vestir-se" which means "to dress oneself".</div><div><strong>vestindo</strong> This is the present participle of the reflexive verb "vestir-se" in Portuguese, which means "to dress oneself". When combined with "estou", it forms a present continuous tense, indicating an action that is currently happening, equivalent to "dressing" in English.</div><div><strong>para</strong> This is a preposition in Portuguese that translates to "for" in English. It’s used here to indicate the purpose of the action.</div><div><strong>a escola</strong> This is a noun phrase where "a" is the definite article "the", and "escola" means "school" in Portuguese. Together, "a escola" means "the school", which is the destination or purpose of the dressing action.</div>','<h2>Sempre me deito depois que ele.</h2><div><strong>Sempre</strong> This is the Portuguese adverb for "always". It indicates that the action is done habitually or without exception.</div><div><strong>me</strong> This is a reflexive pronoun in Portuguese equivalent to "myself" in English. It’s used here with the verb "deito" (I lay down) to indicate that the speaker is performing the action on themselves.</div><div><strong>deito</strong> This comes from the Portuguese verb "deitar", which means "to lay down". It is conjugated in the first-person singular present indicative, "I lay down".</div><div><strong>depois</strong> This is the Portuguese adverb meaning "after". It’s used to indicate that the action of laying down happens subsequent to another action or event.</div><div><strong>que</strong> This Portuguese conjunction is equivalent to "that" in English. Combined with "depois", it creates the expression "depois que" (after that), which is used to introduce a subordinate clause describing the event after which the main action occurs.</div><div><strong>ele</strong> This is the third-person singular pronoun in Portuguese, meaning "he". It serves as the subject of the subordinate clause and refers to another person whose action or situation the speaker’s action is dependent on.</div>','<h2>Eu me penteio antes de sair.</h2><div><strong>Eu</strong> This is the first-person singular pronoun in Portuguese, equivalent to "I" in English. It’s the subject of the sentence.</div><div><strong>me</strong> This is a reflexive pronoun in Portuguese, used here with the reflexive verb "penteio" to indicate that the subject performs the action on itself. The meaning translates to "myself" in English.</div><div><strong>penteio</strong> It comes from the verb "pentear", which means "to comb". In this form, "penteio" is the first-person singular present tense, meaning "I comb". Since it is used with "me", it becomes a reflexive verb, thus "I comb myself".</div><div><strong>antes de</strong> This is a preposition phrase in Portuguese that means "before" in English. It’s used to describe an action that takes place prior to another action.</div><div><strong>sair</strong> This is the infinitive form of the verb "sair", which means "to leave" or "to go out" in English. In this sentence, it indicates the action that happens after the subject combs themselves.</div>','<h2>Tu te sentas para ler.</h2><div><strong>Tu</strong> This is the second-person singular pronoun in Portuguese, equivalent to "you" in English. It’s the subject of the sentence, typically used in informal situations.</div><div><strong>te</strong> This is a reflexive pronoun in Portuguese. It is used here to indicate that the action of the verb is being performed by the subject (you) onto itself. It’s the same person as the subject pronoun "tu".</div><div><strong>sentas</strong> This is the second-person singular present tense form of the verb "sentar", which means "to sit". It implies that the action of sitting is being done by the subject of the sentence.</div><div><strong>para</strong> This is a preposition in Portuguese that can be translated to "for" or "to" in English. In this case, it is used to indicate the purpose of the action.</div><div><strong>ler</strong> This is the infinitive form of the verb "ler" in Portuguese, which means "to read". It is used here to denote the activity for which the action of sitting is performed.</div>','<h2>Tu te lembras?</h2><div><strong>Tu</strong> This is the second-person singular pronoun in Portuguese, equivalent to "you" in English when addressing one person informally.</div><div><strong>te</strong> This is a reflexive pronoun that corresponds to the second-person singular, "yourself" in English. In the sentence, it is used to indicate that the action of the verb is performed by the subject on themselves.</div><div><strong>lembras?</strong> This is the second-person singular form of the present indicative tense of the verb "lembrar", which means "to remember". The question mark indicates that it is a question, asking if the person remembers something.</div>','<h2>Tu te banhas com água fria.</h2><div><strong>Tu</strong> This is the second-person singular pronoun in Portuguese, equivalent to "you" in English when addressing someone informally. It’s the subject of the sentence.</div><div><strong>te</strong> This is a reflexive pronoun in Portuguese, equivalent to "yourself" in English. It’s used here to indicate that the subject (you) is performing the action upon itself.</div><div><strong>banhas</strong> This is the second-person singular present tense form of the verb "banhar", which means "to bathe". In this sentence, it implies the action of bathing is being performed by the subject.</div><div><strong>com</strong> This is a preposition in Portuguese that means "with" in English. It is used here to indicate the accompaniment or the means by which the action is being performed.</div><div><strong>água</strong> This is a noun in Portuguese meaning "water". It’s the direct object of the sentence, receiving the action of bathing.</div><div><strong>fria</strong> This is an adjective in Portuguese meaning "cold". It describes the temperature of the water and agrees in gender and number with the noun it modifies, "água", which is feminine singular.</div>','<h2>Nós nos levantamos de bom humor.</h2><div><strong>Nós</strong> This is the plural first-person pronoun in Portuguese, equivalent to "we" in English. It’s the subject of the sentence.</div><div><strong>nos</strong> This is a reflexive pronoun in Portuguese, equivalent to "ourselves" in English. It reflects the action of the verb back onto the subject.</div><div><strong>levantamos</strong> This is the first-person plural present tense form of the verb "levantar", which means "to get up" or "to rise". It indicates the action performed by the subject.</div><div><strong>de</strong> This is a preposition in Portuguese, which can have several meanings, depending on the context. In this sentence, it means "with" to express the manner in which the action is performed.</div><div><strong>bom</strong> This is a Portuguese adjective meaning "good". It qualifies the mood in which the action was done.</div><div><strong>humor</strong> This is a noun in Portuguese that translates to "mood". Here, it completes the prepositional phrase "de bom humor", meaning "in a good mood".</div>','<h2>Nós nos barbeamos todos os dias.</h2><div><strong>Nós</strong> This is the first-person plural pronoun in Portuguese, equivalent to "we" in English. It is the subject of the sentence.</div><div><strong>nos</strong> This is a reflexive pronoun in Portuguese, used here to indicate that the subjects perform the action on themselves. It is equivalent to "ourselves" in English.</div><div><strong>barbeamos</strong> This is the first-person plural present tense form of the verb "barbear", which means "to shave". In this sentence, it is used reflexively, indicating that the action is being performed by the subjects on themselves.</div><div><strong>todos os dias</strong> This phrase means "every day" in English. "Todos" means "every/all", "os" is the masculine plural definite article "the", and "dias" means "days". Together, it specifies the frequency of the action.</div>','<h2>Nós nos recostamos no sofá.</h2><div><strong>Nós</strong> This is the first-person plural pronoun in Portuguese, equivalent to "we" in English. It’s the subject of the sentence.</div><div><strong>nos</strong> This is a reflexive pronoun in Portuguese, used here to indicate that the subject is performing an action on themselves. It translates to "ourselves" in this context.</div><div><strong>recostamos</strong> This is the first-person plural of the past tense for the verb "recostar", which means "to lean back" or "to recline". It describes the action performed by the subject.</div><div><strong>no</strong> This is a contraction of the preposition "em" (in) + the definite article "o" (the), which together mean "on the" in English.</div><div><strong>sofá</strong> This is a noun in Portuguese which means "sofa" or "couch" in English. It is the object on which the action is being performed.</div>','<h2>Ele se barbeia toda manhã.</h2><div><strong>Ele</strong> This is the third-person singular pronoun in Portuguese, equivalent to "he" in English. It’s the subject of the sentence.</div><div><strong>se</strong> This is a reflexive pronoun in Portuguese, used here to indicate that the subject of the verb performs the action to himself. It is part of the reflexive verb structure "se barbear", which means "to shave oneself".</div><div><strong>barbeia</strong> This is the third-person singular present tense form of the verb "barbear", which means "to shave". In this reflexive construction, it means "he shaves".</div><div><strong>toda manhã</strong> This phrase translates to "every morning" in English. "Toda" means "every" and "manhã" means "morning", indicating the frequency with which the action of shaving occurs.</div>','<h2>Ela não se importa com seu trabalho.</h2><div><strong>Ela</strong> This is the third-person singular pronoun in Portuguese, equivalent to "she" in English. It’s the subject of the sentence.</div><div><strong>não</strong> This is the Portuguese word for "no". It negates a statement or responds negatively to a question.</div><div><strong>se importa</strong> This is a reflexive verb construction. "Se" is a reflexive pronoun, and "importa" is the third-person singular of the present tense form of the verb "importar", which means "to care" or "to mind". Together, they mean "she does not care" or "she is not concerned".</div><div><strong>com</strong> This word translates to "with" in English. It’s a preposition used to indicate a relationship or association.</div><div><strong>seu</strong> This is a possessive pronoun in Portuguese, which can mean "his", "her", "its", or "your" in English, depending on context. In this case, "seu" is likely to mean "her" due to the subject "Ela" which is feminine.</div><div><strong>trabalho</strong> This is a Portuguese noun meaning "work" or "job". Here, it’s the object of the preposition "com", indicating what the subject does not care about.</div>','<h2>Você se deita tarde.</h2><div><strong>Você</strong> This is the second-person singular pronoun in Portuguese, equivalent to "you" in English. It is used to address one person informally.</div><div><strong>se</strong> This is a reflexive pronoun in Portuguese. In this sentence, it refers back to "você" and is part of the verb phrase "se deitar", which means "to lie down" or "to go to bed".</div><div><strong>deita</strong> This is the third-person singular present tense form of the verb "deitar", which means "to lie down". In combination with the reflexive pronoun "se", it forms a reflexive verb meaning "you lie down" or "you go to bed".</div><div><strong>tarde</strong> This is a Portuguese adverb meaning "late". It describes the time when the action of lying down is taking place.</div>','<h2>Vocês estão se olhando no espelho.</h2><div><strong>Vocês</strong> This is the Portuguese second-person plural pronoun equivalent to "you" in English when addressing more than one person.</div><div><strong>estão</strong> This is the second-person plural of the present tense of the verb "estar", which means "to be" in English. It is used to indicate a temporary state or location.</div><div><strong>se</strong> This is a reflexive pronoun used with reflexive verbs. It indicates that the action is being done to oneself, i.e., the subjects are performing the action on themselves.</div><div><strong>olhando</strong> This is the gerund form of the verb "olhar", which means "looking" in English. It describes an ongoing action.</div><div><strong>no</strong> This is a contraction of the preposition "em" (in) and the definite article "o" (the), which together translate to "in the" in English.</div><div><strong>espelho</strong> This is a Portuguese noun meaning "mirror" in English.</div>','<h2>Eles se lembrarão de suas férias.</h2><div><strong>Eles</strong> This is the third-person plural pronoun in Portuguese, equivalent to "they" in English. It’s the subject of the sentence.</div><div><strong>se</strong> This is a reflexive pronoun used in Portuguese to indicate that the action of the verb reflects back on the subject. In this case, it is part of the reflexive verb structure "lembrar-se", which means "to remember".</div><div><strong>lembrarão</strong> This is the third-person plural future tense form of the reflexive verb "lembrar-se", meaning "they will remember". It indicates a future action related to the subject "eles".</div><div><strong>de</strong> This is a preposition in Portuguese often translated to "of" or "about" in English. Here, it is used before "suas férias" to indicate what they will remember.</div><div><strong>suas</strong> This is a possessive adjective in Portuguese, meaning "their" in English. It agrees in gender and number with the noun it qualifies, which in this case is "férias" (holidays/vacation).</div><div><strong>férias</strong> This is a noun in Portuguese meaning "vacation" or "holidays" in English. It is in the plural form, referring to the vacation period they will remember.</div>','<h2>Elas estão se preparando para a próxima corrida.</h2><div><strong>Elas</strong> This is the third-person plural pronoun in Portuguese, equivalent to "they" in English when referring to a group of females or a mixed-gender group where females are included. It’s the subject of the sentence.</div><div><strong>estão</strong> This is the third-person plural of the present tense of the verb "estar", which means "to be" in the context of a temporary state or location. It describes the ongoing state of the subject.</div><div><strong>se preparando</strong> This is a reflexive verb construction which combines "se", a reflexive pronoun, and "preparando", which is the present participle of the verb "preparar", meaning "to prepare" in English. Together, this phrase means "preparing themselves". The addition of "se" gives the sentence the reflexive context needed in Portuguese, indicating that the action is being performed by the subjects upon themselves.</div><div><strong>para</strong> This preposition translates to "for" in English. It’s used to indicate purpose or direction towards something.</div><div><strong>a</strong> This is the definite article in Portuguese, which corresponds to "the" in English. It’s used here to refer specifically to the next item mentioned, which is "corrida".</div><div><strong>próxima</strong> This is an adjective in Portuguese meaning "next" in English. It qualifies the noun that follows it, indicating the subsequent occurrence of whatever is being mentioned.</div><div><strong>corrida</strong> This is the Portuguese word for "race", as in a competitive running event or similar contest of speed. It’s the noun being modified by "próxima", making it the main topic of the sentence. The sentence translates to "They are preparing for the next race".</div>'];var defBonus = ['<h2>Sim, eu acabei de me mudar para cá.</h2><div><strong>Sim</strong> This is the Portuguese word for "yes". It is used to affirmatively respond to a question or to agree with a statement.</div><div><strong>eu</strong> This is the first-person singular pronoun in Portuguese, equivalent to "I" in English. It’s the subject of the sentence.</div><div><strong>acabei</strong> This is the first-person singular past tense form of the verb "acabar", which means "to finish" or "to end". In this context, it is used to indicate that the speaker has recently completed an action.</div><div><strong>de</strong> This preposition in Portuguese is commonly used to indicate the infinitive form of the verbs that follow it. Here, it is part of the verbal phrase "acabei de", which sets the tense of the action.</div><div><strong>me</strong> This is a reflexive pronoun in Portuguese. It refers back to the subject ("eu") and is used here with the verb "mudar" to express that the subject has moved him/herself.</div><div><strong>mudar</strong> This is the infinitive form of the verb in Portuguese which means "to move" or "to change". When used together with the reflexive pronoun "me", it means "to move (myself)" or "to relocate".</div><div><strong>para</strong> This is a preposition in Portuguese meaning "to" or "for". It’s used here to indicate the direction or the destination of the move.</div><div><strong>cá</strong> This is a colloquial Portuguese adverb meaning "here" or "this place". It’s used to refer to the current location or context of the speaker.</div>','<h2>Mas eu quero aprender, não me divertir.</h2><div><strong>Mas</strong> This is the Portuguese conjunction for "but". It’s used to contrast or oppose two ideas or statements.</div><div><strong>eu</strong> This is the first-person singular pronoun in Portuguese, equivalent to "I" in English. It’s the subject of the sentence.</div><div><strong>quero</strong> This is the first-person singular present tense form of the verb "querer", which means "to want". It indicates the speaker’s desire or wish.</div><div><strong>aprender</strong> This is the infinitive form of the verb "aprender", which means "to learn". In this sentence, it’s the direct object of the verb "quero", showing what the speaker wants to do.</div><div><strong>não</strong> This is the Portuguese word for "not". It’s used here to negate the following verb and indicate what the speaker does not want to do.</div><div><strong>me</strong> This is a reflexive pronoun in Portuguese, corresponding to "myself" in English. It is used with the verb "divertir" to indicate that the action pertains to the speaker.</div><div><strong>divertir</strong> This is the infinitive form of the verb "divertir", which means "to entertain" or "to have fun". In this context, it’s paired with "não" and "me" to specify what the speaker is not inclined to do.</div>','<h2>Eu me alongo antes de correr.</h2><div><strong>Eu</strong> This is the first-person singular pronoun in Portuguese, equivalent to "I" in English. It’s the subject of the sentence.</div><div><strong>me</strong> This is a reflexive pronoun in Portuguese, referring back to the subject of the sentence, "Eu". It corresponds to "myself" in English and is used here with a reflexive verb.</div><div><strong>alongo</strong> This is the first-person singular present tense form of the verb "alongar", which means "to stretch". Here it describes the action the subject is performing on themselves.</div><div><strong>antes de</strong> This is a prepositional phrase in Portuguese meaning "before". It is used to indicate that the action of stretching occurs prior to another action.</div><div><strong>correr</strong> This is the infinitive form of the verb "correr", which means "to run". Following "antes de", it denotes the activity that will take place after stretching.</div>','<h2>Eu me sentei aqui para falar ao telefone.</h2><div><strong>Eu</strong> This is the first-person singular pronoun in Portuguese, equivalent to "I" in English. It’s the subject of the sentence.</div><div><strong>me sentei</strong> This is a reflexive verbal phrase in the past tense, combining the reflexive pronoun "me" and the verb "sentar", which means "to sit". Together, they mean "I sat".</div><div><strong>aqui</strong> This is an adverb of place in Portuguese, meaning "here". It indicates the location where the action of sitting took place.</div><div><strong>para</strong> This is a preposition in Portuguese that can be translated as "to" or "in order to" in English. It’s used here to express purpose.</div><div><strong>falar</strong> This is the infinitive form of the verb "to speak" in Portuguese. Following "para", it contributes to the expression of purpose: "in order to speak".</div><div><strong>ao</strong> This is the contraction of the preposition "a" (to) with the masculine singular article "o" (the), equivalent to "to the" in English.</div><div><strong>telefone</strong> This is a masculine noun in Portuguese that means "telephone". It is what the subject intends to speak to.</div>','<h2>Eu sou o seu pai. Eu me preocupo com você.</h2><div><strong>Eu</strong> This is the first-person singular pronoun in Portuguese, equivalent to "I" in English. It’s the subject of both sentences.</div><div><strong>sou</strong> This is the first-person singular present tense form of the verb "ser", which means "to be". It describes the state of being or identity of the subject.</div><div><strong>o</strong> This is the definitive article in Portuguese, equivalent to "the" in English. It is masculine singular, matching with "pai" (father).</div><div><strong>seu</strong> This is the possessive pronoun in Portuguese, meaning "your". It signifies a belonging or relation to the person being addressed (você).</div><div><strong>pai</strong> This is a Portuguese noun meaning "father".</div><div><strong>me</strong> This is a reflexive pronoun in Portuguese, meaning "myself". It’s part of the reflexive verb construction "preocupo-me" (I worry), showing that the speaker is carrying out the action of worrying on themselves, which implies they’re worrying about the listener.</div><div><strong>preocupo</strong> This is the first-person singular present tense form of the verb "preocupar", which means "to worry". In combination with "me", it becomes a reflexive verb "preocupo-me" (I worry).</div><div><strong>com</strong> This is a Portuguese preposition meaning "with". It’s used here to link the verb "preocupo" and the pronoun "você", forming the sense of concern <em>for</em> someone.</div><div><strong>você</strong> This is the second-person singular pronoun in Portuguese, equivalent to "you" in English. In Brazil, it’s commonly used as a respectful and sometimes formal way of addressing someone.</div>','<h2>Tomei banho e logo me vesti.</h2><div><strong>Tomei</strong> This is the first-person singular of the past tense of the verb "tomar" in Portuguese, which means "to take". Here, it’s used in the context of taking a shower or bath.</div><div><strong>banho</strong> This is a noun in Portuguese that means "bath" or "shower". Following "tomei", it indicates the action that took place.</div><div><strong>e</strong> This is the Portuguese word for "and". It’s a conjunction used to connect phrases or clauses.</div><div><strong>logo</strong> This word translates to "soon", "then", or "afterwards" in English. In this sentence, it’s used to indicate an action that took place immediately following the previous one.</div><div><strong>me</strong> This is a reflexive pronoun in Portuguese and means "myself" when translated into English. Here, it indicates that the action of dressing was performed by the speaker on themselves.</div><div><strong>vesti</strong> This is the first-person singular of the past tense of the verb "vestir" in Portuguese, meaning "to dress". Combined with the reflexive pronoun "me", it means "I dressed (myself)".</div>','<h2>Estava quente o suficiente! Eu me diverti!</h2><div><strong>Estava</strong> This is the third-person singular of the verb "estar" in the imperfect tense in Portuguese, meaning "was". It indicates a past state or condition.</div><div><strong>quente</strong> This is a Portuguese adjective meaning "hot". In the sentence, it describes the temperature.</div><div><strong>o suficiente</strong> This is a phrase in Portuguese meaning "enough" or "sufficiently". It qualifies the adjective to indicate that something was to an adequate degree.</div><div><strong>Eu</strong> This is the first-person singular pronoun in Portuguese, equivalent to "I" in English. It’s the subject of the next sentence.</div><div><strong>me</strong> This is a reflexive pronoun in Portuguese, used here with the verb "divertir" to indicate that the subject is performing the action on themselves, equivalent to "myself" in English.</div><div><strong>diverti</strong> This is the first-person singular past tense (preterite) form of the verb "divertir", which means "to enjoy" or "to have fun". The sentence translates to "I had fun" or "I enjoyed myself".</div>','<h2>Eu me vesti para trabalhar, mas não trabalho hoje.</h2><div><strong>Eu</strong> This is the first-person singular pronoun in Portuguese, equivalent to "I" in English. It’s the subject of the sentence.</div><div><strong>me vesti</strong> This is the first-person singular past tense form of the reflexive verb "vestir-se", which means "to dress oneself". It indicates that the subject dressed themselves.</div><div><strong>para</strong> This is a preposition in Portuguese meaning "for" or "to". It indicates purpose or direction.</div><div><strong>trabalhar</strong> This is the infinitive form of the verb "trabalhar", which means "to work". Following "para", it indicates the purpose of the action (dressing oneself) was to go to work.</div><div><strong>mas</strong> This is a conjunction in Portuguese meaning "but". It’s used to introduce a contrasting statement.</div><div><strong>não</strong> This is the Portuguese word for "no" or "not". It negates the following verb.</div><div><strong>trabalho</strong> This is the first-person singular present tense form of the verb "trabalhar", meaning "to work". Here, it indicates the current state or action of the subject.</div><div><strong>hoje</strong> This is the Portuguese word for "today". It specifies the time frame in which the action of not working is taking place.</div>','<h2>Eu me aproximei da lareira porque estava com frio.</h2><div><strong>Eu</strong> This is the first-person singular pronoun in Portuguese, equivalent to "I" in English. It’s the subject of the sentence.</div><div><strong>me aproximei</strong> This is the first-person singular past tense form of the reflexive verb "aproximar-se", which means "to approach". The "me" indicates the reflexive action, showing that the subject performed the action on themselves.</div><div><strong>da</strong> This is a contraction of the Portuguese preposition "de" (of, from) with the definite article "a" (the), which together mean "from the" or "of the". It’s used to refer to something in a specific context here with "lareira" (fireplace).</div><div><strong>lareira</strong> This is a Portuguese noun meaning "fireplace". It is the object of the action, indicating where the subject approached.</div><div><strong>porque</strong> This is a conjunction in Portuguese meaning "because". It introduces a cause or a reason.</div><div><strong>estava</strong> This is the first-person singular imperfect tense of the verb "estar", which means "to be" in Portuguese. It describes a past continuous state or condition.</div><div><strong>com</strong> This Portuguese preposition translates to "with" in English. It’s used to indicate possession or accompaniment.</div><div><strong>frio</strong> This is a Portuguese adjective meaning "cold". Here, it’s used as a noun to describe the speaker’s condition or sensation.</div>','<h2>Eu me lembrei do horário errado e esqueci a passagem em casa.</h2><div><strong>Eu</strong> This is the first-person singular pronoun in Portuguese, equivalent to "I" in English. It’s the subject of the sentence.</div><div><strong>me</strong> This is a reflexive pronoun in Portuguese, used here with the verb "lembrei" to indicate that the action is done by the subject to themselves. In English, "myself" might be used.</div><div><strong>lembrei</strong> This is the first-person singular past tense form of the verb "lembrar", which means "to remember". Here, it’s used in the reflexive form to say "I remembered".</div><div><strong>do</strong> This is a contraction of the preposition "de" (meaning "of" or "from") and the definite article "o" (meaning "the"). In English, "of the" or "from the" would be used. It’s here to express what was remembered—in this case, the wrong time.</div><div><strong>horário</strong> This is a noun in Portuguese that means "schedule" or "time". In this context, it refers to a specific time that was remembered incorrectly.</div><div><strong>errado</strong> This is an adjective in Portuguese meaning "wrong" or "incorrect". It’s used here to describe the time that was remembered.</div><div><strong>e</strong> This is a conjunction in Portuguese that means "and". It is used to connect phrases or clauses.</div><div><strong>esqueci</strong> This is the first-person singular past tense form of the verb "esquecer", which means "to forget". It indicates that the subject forgot something.</div><div><strong>a</strong> This is the definite article in Portuguese, feminine singular form of "the". It’s used here to introduce the noun "passagem".</div><div><strong>passagem</strong> This is a noun in Portuguese that means "ticket" or "passage". In this context, it refers to a ticket that was forgotten.</div><div><strong>em</strong> This is a preposition in Portuguese that translates to "in" in English. It’s used to indicate location or position.</div><div><strong>casa</strong> This means "home" or "house" in Portuguese. When combined with the preposition "em", it means "at home" in this context.</div>','<h2>Se não tivesse um mapa, eu me perderia.</h2><div><strong>Se</strong> This is a conjunction in Portuguese that introduces a conditional clause, equivalent to "if" in English.</div><div><strong>não</strong> This is the Portuguese word for "not". It negates the condition being discussed in the sentence.</div><div><strong>tivesse</strong> This is the first-person singular imperfect subjunctive form of the verb "ter", which means "to have". In the sentence, it indicates a hypothetical situation in the past: "had" or "were to have".</div><div><strong>um mapa</strong> This means "a map" in Portuguese. "Um" is a masculine singular indefinite article, and "mapa" is the noun for map.</div><div><strong>eu</strong> This is the first-person singular pronoun in Portuguese, equivalent to "I" in English. It’s the subject of the main clause.</div><div><strong>me perderia</strong> This is a verb phrase using the first-person singular conditional tense of "perder-se", which means "to get lost" or "would get lost". The reflexive pronoun "me" indicates that the action refers back to the subject ("eu"), indicating that the person would get lost themselves.</div>','<h2>Se tivesse terminado minhas tarefas, eu me divertiria.</h2><div><strong>Se</strong> This is a conjunction in Portuguese, equivalent to "if" in English. It introduces a conditional clause, indicating a hypothetical situation.</div><div><strong>tivesse</strong> This is the first-person singular past subjunctive tense of the verb "ter", which means "to have" in English. It is used here to express an action that could have happened but did not in the past.</div><div><strong>terminado</strong> This is the past participle of the verb "terminar", which means "to finish" or "to complete" in English. It refers to the action of finishing and is used with the auxiliary verb "tivesse" in this conditional phrase.</div><div><strong>minhas</strong> This is a possessive pronoun in Portuguese, equivalent to "my" in English. It indicates ownership or association with the speaker, and here it qualifies "tarefas" (tasks).</div><div><strong>tarefas,</strong> This is the noun for "tasks" in Portuguese, equivalent to "tasks" in English. It is in the plural form and is the object of the conditional clause indicating what the speaker could have finished.</div><div><strong>eu</strong> This is the first-person singular pronoun in Portuguese, equivalent to "I" in English. It’s the subject of the main clause in this conditional sentence.</div><div><strong>me</strong> This is a reflexive pronoun in Portuguese, equivalent to "myself" in English. It is used with the verb "divertir" to express that the action is performed by and affects the speaker.</div><div><strong>divertiria</strong> This is the first-person singular conditional tense of the verb "divertir", which means "to enjoy oneself" or "to have fun" in English. It describes an action that would happen under certain conditions, which in this case refers to the hypothetical completion of the speaker’s tasks.</div>','<h2>Me incomoda que te preocupes tanto.</h2><div><strong>Me</strong> This is a reflexive pronoun in Portuguese, used here in the accusative case. It indicates that the action of the verb "incomoda" (bothers) is affecting the speaker.</div><div><strong>incomoda</strong> This is the third-person singular present tense form of the verb "incomodar", which means "to bother" or "to discomfort". In this sentence, it is conjugated to agree with an implicit subject that refers to a certain situation or thing that is causing the bother.</div><div><strong>que</strong> This is a conjunction in Portuguese that often introduces subordinated clauses. In this sentence, it introduces a clause that explains the reason for the bother.</div><div><strong>te</strong> This is a reflexive pronoun in Portuguese, used here in the accusative case. It indicates that the action of the verb "preocupes" (worry) is directed at the person being spoken to.</div><div><strong>preocupes</strong> This is the second-person singular present subjunctive tense of the verb "preocupar", which means "to worry". The subjunctive mood is used because the sentence expresses a reaction to an uncertain or hypothetical situation: the speaker’s worry.</div><div><strong>tanto</strong> This is an adverb in Portuguese that means "so much" or "this much". It indicates the intensity or degree of the worry that is bothering the speaker.</div>','<h2>Tu te deitaste muito cedo noite passada.</h2><div><strong>Tu</strong> This is the second-person singular pronoun in Portuguese, equivalent to "you" in English. It is the subject of the sentence and used in informal situations.</div><div><strong>te</strong> This is a reflexive pronoun that, in this sentence, is part of the reflexive verb construction. It refers back to the subject "tu" and means "yourself".</div><div><strong>deitaste</strong> This is the second-person singular past tense form of the verb "deitar", which means "to lay down". In the context of this sentence, it indicates an action completed in the past.</div><div><strong>muito</strong> This is an adverb meaning "very" in English. It is modifying the adverb "cedo" to express the intensity of how early the subject went to bed.</div><div><strong>cedo</strong> This is an adverb meaning "early" in English. It describes the time at which the subject went to bed.</div><div><strong>noite passada</strong> This phrase means "last night" in English. "Noite" is the noun "night", and "passada" is the feminine past participle of "passar", meaning "past", agreeing in gender with "noite".</div>','<h2>Acho que tu estás te enganando quanto a isso.</h2><div><strong>Acho</strong> This is the first-person singular present tense form of the verb "achar", which means "to think" or "to believe" in Portuguese.</div><div><strong>que</strong> This is a conjunction in Portuguese that means "that". It is used to link the verbs and introduce a subordinate clause.</div><div><strong>tu</strong> This is the second-person singular pronoun in Portuguese, equivalent to "you" in English. It is the subject of the subordinate clause.</div><div><strong>estás</strong> This is the second-person singular present tense form of the verb "estar", which means "to be" in Portuguese, indicating a temporary state or condition.</div><div><strong>te</strong> This is a reflexive pronoun in Portuguese. It is used with reflexive verbs and translates to "yourself" in English, indicating that the subject performs an action on itself.</div><div><strong>enganando</strong> This is the present participle form of the verb "enganar", which means "to deceive" or "to fool" in Portuguese. In this construction, it’s being used to form the present continuous tense – "te enganando" translates to "deceiving yourself".</div><div><strong>quanto</strong> This word can have several meanings in Portuguese, but in this context, it means "about" or "regarding". It introduces the subject of the deception.</div><div><strong>a isso</strong> "A isso" translates to "to this" or "about this" in English. The preposition "a" combined with the neuter pronoun "isso" refers to something previously mentioned or understood in the context of the conversation.</div>','<h2>Se tivesses te deitado mais cedo, acordarias bem descansada.</h2><div><strong>Se</strong> This is the Portuguese word for "if". It is used to introduce a conditional clause, which expresses a condition that could lead to a different outcome.</div><div><strong>tivesses</strong> This is the second-person singular form of the imperfect subjunctive tense of the verb "ter", which means "to have". In this context, it’s part of a conditional clause referring to an event that didn’t happen in the past ("if you had").</div><div><strong>te deitado</strong> This phrase combines the reflexive pronoun "te" with the past participle "deitado" of the verb "deitar", which means "to lay down" or "go to bed". Together it translates to "laid down yourself" or "gone to bed", as in "if you had gone to bed".</div><div><strong>mais cedo</strong> This means "earlier". It is an adverbial phrase indicating when the action of going to bed should have occurred.</div><div><strong>acordarias</strong> This is the second-person singular form of the conditional tense of the verb "acordar", which means "to wake up". In this context, it suggests the outcome that would have occurred if the previous condition had been met ("you would wake up").</div><div><strong>bem</strong> This is an adverb meaning "well". It is used to describe the manner in which the subject would wake up.</div><div><strong>descansada</strong> This is a Portuguese adjective meaning "rested" in a feminine singular form, modifying how the subject would feel upon waking ("well rested"). If referring to a male subject, it would be "descansado".</div>','<h2>Se não tivesses uma memória tão ruim, te lembrarias das direções.</h2><div><strong>Se</strong> This is the Portuguese conditional conjunction meaning "if". It introduces a conditional clause.</div><div><strong>não</strong> This is the Portuguese word for "not". It negates the statement that follows.</div><div><strong>tivesses</strong> This is the second-person singular past subjunctive form of the verb "ter", which means "to have". Here it is used in a conditional sense as part of the phrase "if you had".</div><div><strong>uma</strong> This is the Portuguese indefinite article meaning "a" or "an" in English, used here in its feminine singular form.</div><div><strong>memória</strong> This is a Portuguese noun meaning "memory". It’s feminine and singular to match the article.</div><div><strong>tão</strong> This is a Portuguese adverb meaning "so" or "such". It’s used here to enhance the adjective that follows.</div><div><strong>ruim</strong> This is a Portuguese adjective meaning "bad" or "poor". Here, it describes the quality of the memory.</div><div><strong>te</strong> This is the Portuguese reflexive pronoun meaning "you", used here to reflect the action back on the subject of the sentence.</div><div><strong>lembrarias</strong> This is the second-person singular conditional form of the verb "lembrar", which means "to remember". It implies what the subject would do under a certain condition.</div><div><strong>das</strong> This is the Portuguese contraction of the preposition "de" (of) and the definite article "as" (the), forming "das" which means "of the" or "from the" in a feminine plural context.</div><div><strong>direções</strong> This is the Portuguese noun meaning "directions". It is a feminine plural noun that follows the preposition-article contraction.</div>','<h2>Estamos nos divertindo na neve.</h2><div><strong>Estamos</strong> This is the first-person plural of the verb "estar" in the present continuous tense, meaning "we are". It indicates an action that is currently in progress.</div><div><strong>nos</strong> This is a reflexive pronoun which translates to "ourselves". In this context, it is part of the reflexive verb construction "divertir-se" which means "to have fun" or "to enjoy oneself".</div><div><strong>divertindo</strong> This is the gerund form of the reflexive verb "divertir-se", meaning "having fun" or "enjoying". Together with "Estamos", it forms the present continuous tense "are having fun" or "are enjoying".</div><div><strong>na</strong> This is a contraction of the preposition "em" (in) and the article "a" (the), which together translate to "in the" in English. It’s used to describe the location where the action is taking place.</div><div><strong>neve</strong> This is a noun meaning "snow". It is the object of the preposition "na", indicating the location where the action of having fun is happening.</div>','<h2>Iremos nos divertir no parque.</h2><div><strong>Iremos</strong> Esta é a forma futura do verbo "ir" em português, que significa "to go" em inglês. Aqui indica uma ação futura, "we will go".</div><div><strong>nos</strong> Este é um pronome reflexivo em português, que se refere ao sujeito da ação (nós). Em inglês, seria equivalente a "ourselves". É usado aqui para indicar que a ação de se divertir é realizada pelas mesmas pessoas que vão ao parque.</div><div><strong>divertir</strong> Este é o verbo "divertir-se" em português, que significa "to have fun" ou "to enjoy oneself" em inglês. A forma "divertir" está no infinitivo porque se segue a conjugação do verbo "ir", formando uma expressão que indica uma intenção ou um plano futuro.</div><div><strong>no</strong> Esta é a contração da preposição "em" com o artigo definido "o" em português, que equivale a "in the" em inglês. É usada aqui para indicar a localização onde a ação vai acontecer.</div><div><strong>parque</strong> Esta é a palavra em português para "park" em inglês. Refere-se ao lugar público ao ar livre onde as pessoas vão para se divertir, fazer atividades recreativas, etc.</div>','<h2>Nós nos lembramos muito bem daquele dia.</h2><div><strong>Nós</strong> This is the first-person plural pronoun in Portuguese, equivalent to "we" in English. It’s the subject of the sentence.</div><div><strong>nos</strong> This is the reflexive pronoun in Portuguese, used here with the verb "lembrar" to indicate that the subjects remember something themselves. It corresponds to "ourselves" in English.</div><div><strong>lembramos</strong> This is the first-person plural present tense form of the verb "lembrar", which means "to remember". It denotes the action of recalling a memory that the subject of the verb is performing.</div><div><strong>muito bem</strong> This phrase means "very well" in English. It’s an adverbial phrase that enhances the verb "lembramos", indicating the quality of how the subjects remember.</div><div><strong>daquele</strong> This is a demonstrative pronoun in Portuguese, meaning "that" in English. It’s used to refer to a specific day in the past which is far from both the speaker and the listener.</div><div><strong>dia</strong> This is a Portuguese noun meaning "day". In this sentence, it’s the direct object of the verb "lembramos", indicating what is being remembered.</div>','<h2>Sim, esse é um dos motivos de nos mudarmos para cá.</h2><div><strong>Sim</strong> This is the Portuguese word for "yes". It confirms a statement or responds affirmatively to a question.</div><div><strong>esse</strong> This is a demonstrative pronoun in Portuguese, equivalent to "that" in English. However, when accompanied by the verb "é" (is), it can often be translated as "this" to refer to something that was recently mentioned or is about to be explained.</div><div><strong>é</strong> This is the third-person singular present tense form of the verb "ser", which means "to be". It describes the state of being or identity.</div><div><strong>um</strong> This is the Portuguese indefinite article for masculine singular nouns, equivalent to "a" or "an" in English.</div><div><strong>dos</strong> This is a contraction of the preposition "de" (of/from) and the definite article "os" (the), used here to mean "of the" or "from the" when referring to plural masculine nouns.</div><div><strong>motivos</strong> This is the Portuguese word for "reasons", in the plural form. It’s the object of the preposition "de" (of/from) in the contraction "dos".</div><div><strong>de nos mudarmos</strong> This phrase combines the preposition "de" with the reflexive pronoun "nos" (us/ourselves) and the infinitive verb "mudarmos" (to move). Together, it means "of us moving", describing the action or process behind the reasons mentioned.</div><div><strong>para</strong> This is a preposition in Portuguese that means "to" or "for" when indicating direction or purpose.</div><div><strong>cá</strong> This is an adverb of place in Portuguese, meaning "here", referring to the place where the speaker is currently located or to the place they have moved.</div>','<h2>Nós nos prepararemos para a festa esta noite.</h2><div><strong>Nós</strong> This is the first-person plural pronoun in Portuguese, equivalent to "we" in English. It’s the subject of the sentence.</div><div><strong>nos</strong> This is a reflexive pronoun in Portuguese, matching the subject "nós" in person and number. It refers back to the subject, indicating that the subject is preparing itself.</div><div><strong>prepararemos</strong> This is the first-person plural future tense form of the verb "preparar", which means "to prepare". It describes an action that will be performed by the subject in the future.</div><div><strong>para a</strong> This is a prepositional phrase in Portuguese. "Para" means "for" and "a" is the feminine singular definite article "the". Together, they are used to indicate direction or purpose, here referring to "the party".</div><div><strong>festa</strong> This is a Portuguese noun meaning "party". It’s feminine and singular to match with the article "a".</div><div><strong>esta</strong> This is a demonstrative pronoun in Portuguese, meaning "this". It is used to specify which night, indicating the one that is current or near.</div><div><strong>noite</strong> This is a Portuguese noun meaning "night". It is feminine and singular, used here to specify the time when the preparation will occur.</div>','<h2>Beberemos uma garrafa de água após nos exercitarmos.</h2><div><strong>Beberemos</strong> This is the first-person plural future tense of the verb "beber", which means "to drink" in Portuguese. It indicates an action that will be performed by "we" in the future.</div><div><strong>uma</strong> This is the indefinite article in Portuguese, equivalent to "a" in English. It’s feminine and singular to agree with "garrafa".</div><div><strong>garrafa</strong> This is a feminine noun in Portuguese meaning "bottle".</div><div><strong>de</strong> This is a preposition in Portuguese that can be translated as "of" in English. It is used here to link "garrafa" with "água".</div><div><strong>água</strong> This noun means "water" in Portuguese. It is a feminine and uncountable noun.</div><div><strong>após</strong> This is a preposition in Portuguese that means "after".</div><div><strong>nos</strong> This is a reflexive pronoun in Portuguese that means "ourselves". It’s used in connection with reflexive verbs, in this case "exercitarmos".</div><div><strong>exercitarmos</strong> This is the first-person plural future subjunctive tense of the verb "exercitar", which means "to exercise". It reflects an action that will potentially be performed by the subject (we) after another action (in this case, drinking water).</div>','<h2>Nós nos vestiremos quando tivermos que sair da casa.</h2><div><strong>Nós</strong> This is the first-person plural pronoun in Portuguese, equivalent to "we" in English. It’s the subject of the sentence.</div><div><strong>nos vestiremos</strong> This is a reflexive verb in the future tense, meaning "we will dress ourselves". "Vestir" is the verb to dress, "nos" is a reflexive pronoun meaning "ourselves" and "emos" is the future tense ending for "we".</div><div><strong>quando</strong> This translates to "when" in English. It introduces a subordinate clause indicating the time at which the action will take place.</div><div><strong>tivermos</strong> This is the first-person plural subjunctive form of the verb "ter", which means "to have" in English. In this context, it helps to form a future subjunctive phrase which is used to express an action that may or may not happen.</div><div><strong>que</strong> This word translates as "that" or "to" in English, depending on the context. Here it’s being used to introduce a necessity or obligation.</div><div><strong>sair</strong> This is the infinitive form of the verb meaning "to leave" or "to go out".</div><div><strong>da casa</strong> This phrase means "from the house" or "of the house" in English, where "da" is a contraction of the preposition "de" (of) and the definite article "a" (the), and "casa" means "house".</div>','<h2>Nós nos sentávamos no chão porque não tínhamos um sofá.</h2><div><strong>Nós</strong> This is the first-person plural pronoun in Portuguese, equivalent to "we" in English. It’s the subject of the sentence.</div><div><strong>nos</strong> This is a reflexive pronoun in Portuguese, which refers back to the subject of the sentence (Nós). It’s used here with the reflexive verb "sentar-se".</div><div><strong>sentávamos</strong> This is the first-person plural imperfect tense form of the reflexive verb "sentar-se", which means "to sit down". The imperfect tense denotes a past action that was ongoing or habitual.</div><div><strong>no</strong> This is a contraction of the preposition "em" (in) and the definite article "o" (the), which together mean "on the" in English. It precedes and combines with "chão" to denote the place where the action of sitting was occurring.</div><div><strong>chão</strong> This is a noun meaning "floor" in Portuguese. It’s used here to indicate the physical place of the action.</div><div><strong>porque</strong> This word translates to "because" in English. It’s a subordinating conjunction used to introduce a cause or reason.</div><div><strong>não</strong> This is the Portuguese word for "not". It negates the verb that follows it, here indicating the absence of something.</div><div><strong>tínhamos</strong> This is the first-person plural imperfect tense form of the verb "ter", which means "to have". Like "sentávamos", the imperfect tense communicates a past habitual condition or ongoing state.</div><div><strong>um</strong> This is a Portuguese indefinite article meaning "a" in English. It’s used here before the noun "sofá" to indicate any sofa, not a specific one.</div><div><strong>sofá</strong> This is a noun meaning "sofa" or "couch" in Portuguese. It’s the object of the sentence and receives the action of the possessive verb "tínhamos" (did not have).</div>','<h2>Elas se deitarão depois da história.</h2><div><strong>Elas</strong> This is a third-person plural pronoun in Portuguese, equivalent to "they" in English when referring to a feminine group or objects. It’s the subject of the sentence.</div><div><strong>se</strong> This is a reflexive pronoun in Portuguese, used here with the verb "deitar" (to lie down) to indicate that the action is performed by the subject onto themselves. In English, the idea of the reflexive is often implicit, but in Portuguese, the reflexive pronoun is necessary.</div><div><strong>deitarão</strong> This is the third-person plural future tense of the verb "deitar", which means "to lie down". It indicates a future action that will be performed by the subject.</div><div><strong>depois</strong> This is an adverb of time in Portuguese, equivalent to "after" in English. It’s used to indicate a sequence of events.</div><div><strong>da</strong> This is a contraction of the preposition "de" (of/from) with the definite article "a" (the), translating to "of the" or "from the" when used with feminine nouns in Portuguese. Here it indicates a possessive relationship, equivalent to "after the" in English.</div><div><strong>história</strong> This is a feminine noun in Portuguese, which means "story". In the given sentence, it is the object of the preposition "depois", completing the phrase for "after the story".</div>','<h2>Ela se deitava depois de ler um pouco.</h2><div><strong>Ela</strong> This is the third-person singular pronoun in Portuguese, equivalent to "she" in English. It’s the subject of the sentence.</div><div><strong>se</strong> This is a reflexive pronoun used in conjunction with the verb "deitava" to indicate that the action is being performed by the subject on herself. In English, it could be translated as "herself" in the context of this action.</div><div><strong>deitava</strong> This is the third-person singular form of the imperfect tense of the verb "deitar", which means "to lie down". In this tense, it implies a repeated or habitual past action, equivalent to "she used to lie down" or "she would lie down" in English.</div><div><strong>depois de</strong> This phrase translates to "after" in English. It is used as a preposition to indicate the relative time in which actions occur.</div><div><strong>ler</strong> This is the infinitive form of the verb "ler", which means "to read" in English.</div><div><strong>um</strong> This is the indefinite article in Portuguese, corresponding to "a" or "an" in English, used here in its masculine form due to the masculine noun it precedes.</div><div><strong>pouco</strong> This word translates to "a little" or "a bit" in English. It is used to describe the extent or duration of the reading.</div>','<h2>Vocês se sentarão no sofá para discutir.</h2><div><strong>Vocês</strong> This is the second-person plural pronoun in Portuguese, equivalent to "you all" in English. It refers to more than one person being addressed.</div><div><strong>se</strong> This is a reflexive pronoun in Portuguese, used here as part of the reflexive verb "sentar-se", which means "to sit down". In this sentence, it implies that the action of sitting is being performed by the subjects (vocês) themselves.</div><div><strong>sentarão</strong> This is the third-person plural future tense of the verb "sentar", which means "to sit". The inclusion of "se" before it changes the meaning to "will sit down", referring to a future action by the subjects.</div><div><strong>no</strong> This is a contraction in Portuguese that combines the preposition "em" (in) with the definite article "o" (the), which becomes "no" when used before a masculine noun. It translates to "on the" or "in the" in English.</div><div><strong>sofá</strong> This is a masculine noun in Portuguese meaning "sofa" or "couch" in English.</div><div><strong>para</strong> This is a preposition in Portuguese that translates to "for" or "in order to" in English. It is used to indicate purpose or goal.</div><div><strong>discutir</strong> This is the infinitive form of the verb "discutir", which means "to discuss" or "to argue" in English. It indicates the action that the subjects will perform while sitting on the sofa.</div>','<h2>Você se divertirá hoje.</h2><div><strong>Você</strong> This is the Portuguese second-person singular pronoun, equivalent to "you" in English. It’s used here as the subject of the sentence.</div><div><strong>se</strong> This is a reflexive pronoun in Portuguese, which in this case is part of the reflexive verb construction (divertir-se) meaning "to have fun" or "to enjoy oneself".</div><div><strong>divertirá</strong> This is the future tense, third-person singular form of the reflexive verb "divertir-se" in Portuguese. It means "will have fun" or "will enjoy oneself". It reflects that the action will happen in the future and that the person performing the action and receiving the action is the same (hence the use of the reflexive).</div><div><strong>hoje</strong> This is the Portuguese word for "today". It indicates the time when the action of enjoying oneself will take place.</div>','<h2>Ela se divertia tirando fotos.</h2><div><strong>Ela</strong> This is the third-person singular pronoun in Portuguese, equivalent to "she" in English. It’s the subject of the sentence.</div><div><strong>se</strong> This is a reflexive pronoun in Portuguese that, in this context, is part of the pronominal verb "se divertir" meaning "to have fun" or "to enjoy oneself". It reflects the action of the verb back onto the subject.</div><div><strong>divertia</strong> This is the third-person singular imperfect tense form of the verb "divertir", which means "to enjoy" or "to have fun". It describes an ongoing past action or a habitual action in the past.</div><div><strong>tirando</strong> This is the gerund form of the verb "tirar", which means "to take". In this sentence, it is used in combination with the verb "divertia" to indicate the action she was enjoying.</div><div><strong>fotos</strong> This is a Portuguese noun meaning "photos". It is the direct object of the verb "tirando", indicating what kind of photos she was taking.</div>','<h2>As crianças se lembrarão desta viagem.</h2><div><strong>As</strong> This is the definite article in Portuguese for feminine plural nouns, equivalent to "the" in English. It specifies a particular group of children in this context.</div><div><strong>crianças</strong> This is a Portuguese noun in the plural form, meaning "children". It is feminine plural to match with the definite article "As".</div><div><strong>se</strong> This is a reflexive pronoun in Portuguese, used here as part of a reflexive verb construction ("lembrar-se"). It refers back to the subject, indicating that the action of remembering is being done by the subject themselves.</div><div><strong>lembrarão</strong> This is the third-person plural of the future tense of the verb "lembrar", which means "to remember". It indicates that the action will happen in the future ("will remember").</div><div><strong>desta</strong> This is a contraction in Portuguese of the preposition "de" (of/from) and the feminine singular definite article "a" (the), translating to "of this" or "from this" in English. It is used to indicate possession or association with the forthcoming noun "viagem".</div><div><strong>viagem</strong> This is a Portuguese noun meaning "trip" or "journey". It is singular and feminine, matching the article and the possessive contraction "desta".</div>'];definitions = definitions.concat(defBonus);